Here is a basic example of how you can implement a function in C++ that converts Markdown to HTML. This function will convert a few basic Markdown syntax such as bold text, italics, headers, links, and lists.

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <regex>
#include <iostream>

std::string markdownToHTML(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html = markdown;

    // bold text
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("\\*([^*]+)\*", std::string("\\<b>\\1&lt;/b>"));
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("\\*_([^_]+)_", std::string("\\<i>\\1&lt;/i>"));

    // headers
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("# (.+)", std::string("\\<h2>\\1&lt;/h2>"));
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("## (.+)", std::string("\\<h3>\\1&lt;/h3>"));
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("### (.+)", std::string("\\<h4>\\1&lt;/h4>"));

    // links
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("\\[([^\]]+)\\]\\(([^)]+)\\)", std::string("\\<a href=\"\\2\">\\1&lt;/a>"));

    // lists
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("^ *([+-])[ \t]+(.*)(?:\n|$)", std::string("\\<ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;\\2&lt;/li&gt;&lt;\\1&gt;&lt;\\/>\\n"));
    html = std::regex_replace(html, std::regex("\\*([^\*]+)", std::string("\\<li>\\1&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;"));

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "# My Heading\n"
                         "## My Subheading\n"
                         "\n"
                         "*This text will be italic*\n"
                         "**This text will be bold**\n"
                         "[This is a link](https://www.example.com)\n"
                         "### My Subsubheading\n"
                         "\n"
                         "+ Item 1\n"
                         "+ Item 2\n"
                         "+ Item 3";
    std::cout << markdownToHTML(markdown) << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

This function uses the `std::regex_replace` function to replace Markdown syntax with HTML syntax. It's a simple example and doesn't cover all possible Markdown syntax, you may want to add more patterns to convert all the Markdown syntax you want to support.

Also note that this function doesn't handle nested syntax, for example it will not correctly parse Markdown which includes bold and italics together.

Remember to include the necessary libraries (`<regex>` and `<iostream>`) and specify the `-lstdc++` flag when compiling with GCC to enable C++11 features which are required for regex.

You can compile this code with the following command:

```bash
g++ -o markdownConverter markdownConverter.cpp -lstdc++
```

